      "note_no": "61",
      "note": "Lit., \"the second of two\": an allusion to the Prophet's flight, in the company of Abu Bakr, from Mecca to Medina in the year 622 of the Christian era. The expression \"the second of two\" does not imply any order of precedence but is synonymous with \"one of two\": cf. the Prophet's saying to Abu Bakr, on that very occasion, \"What [could], in thy opinion, [happen] to two [men] who have God as the third with them?\" (Bukhari, in the chapter Fada'il Ashab an-Nabi)."
